Christopher Whall window at Holy Trinity

Adjacent to a 16th century Gate House

Set on a hillside, its 52 acres of woodland provides a green breathing space offering peace and tranquillity.  Imposing tombs contrast with the tumbling headstones and carved angels peer through a covering of ivy. Visits to chapel and crypt.

Occupied by the Royal Naval College from 1869 to 1998, it is now a premier historic, cultural and educational destination in the heart of the Maritime Greenwich UNESCO World Heritage Site.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College

properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Mary Court

Richmond Lock &Weir consists of three 32 ton weir gates that operate 2 hours either side of high water.

Join a tour led by a Chelsea Pensioner to learn about the site's history, including architectural contributions from Sir Christopher Wren & Sir John Soane. Discover the New Soane Stable Yard and its interactive exhibition for deeper insights  into the RHC's rich history.
properties.name: Royal Hospital Chelsea, Home of the Chelsea Pensioners

https://www.soane.org/whats-on

properties.description: A Grade 2-listed mid-Victorian parish church in the Gothic style,  built of Kentish ragstone with a slate roof.  Unique features include a panel of hand-made decorated tiles beyond the High Altar - probably Royal Doulton - and five noted stained glass windows, probably by Alfred Hemming.  The baptistery is also noteworthy, with its font and five murals of Biblical scenes, painted in oil on canvas.

A good quality well used organ in good condition, and excellent acoustics.

properties.description:
Discover how South Kensington, nicknamed "Albertopolis", developed into London’s first district dedicated to arts and science as the British Empire reached its peak. 

By exploring the area's architecture, we'll decode the symbols which asserted the dominance of Western ideas and technology, as well as the power of the British Empire and its monarchy.

images.title: The Monument to the Exhibition of 1851 and the Royal Albert Hall/Joanna Oyediran

properties.description: The walk will start at the Old Operating Museum in Southwark and finish near Waterloo station, taking in major landmarks such as the Shard, or the former Bethlehem Hospital, alongside little known gems such as Octavia Hill's cottages for the poor. Built by Maxwell Fry in 1937 it is the first example of modernist housing for working class people in the UK. Invaluable design input from Elizabeth Denby to create an 'urban village' around the footprint of Gasworks, with innovative community spaces

Construction is underway, with completion expected by summer 2023.

The church itself has been Grade II* listed since 1976.

The only building in Lambeth with two blue plaques, the last building squatted by Olive Morris, final home of CLR James, windows by legendary designer Jon Daniel. The oldest Advice Centre in London. Offices of the Race Today Collective. See how we are still on the Frontline of Brixton and changing lives.

properties.description: Our Clubhouse has a hidden history - it was once the changing rooms for the Crystal Palace Park Concert Bowl. Rock ‘n’ roll legends such as Lou Reed, Elton John, Pink Floyd and many others prepared for their shows in this former park keepers hut.   In 1997 the hut was moved to our allotment site to become a community hub. We are holding an Open Day to celebrate the  recent refurbishment.

images.title: Drone photograph of the Clubhouse prior to refurbishment by David Miller.

properties.name: The Clubhouse at Dorset Road Allotments

properties.description: In the 19th century there were 52 pubs within 20 minutes of Kingston’s Market place. Our walking tour explores the history of brewing and drinking in Kingston, from Roman times to the present day.
properties.name: Pubs of Old Kingston

properties.description: Grade 2 star listed Arts and Crafts gem  designed by Baillie-Scott
properties.name: 1 Waterlow Court

properties.description: This tour will look into the diverse buildings,their stories, styles and their effects on the Croydon Old Town/Central Croydon. From medieval churches to Brutalism, 1960s urban planning and Victorian green spaces, this tour will span the history of Croydon and discuss what it might look like in the future.
properties.name: Central Croydon- Stories, Styles & Spaces

properties.description: Stroll through beautiful Upper Shirley. Discover the area's ancient woodland, discuss nearby grand manor houses, pass by the windmill, ending at The Wilderness garden, a historic therapeutic garden and nursing home updated for the 21st century.
properties.name: Upper Shirley walking tour

properties.description:
The Landmark Trust is a national building conservation charity that restores historic properties at risk and turns them into accommodation for unique short breaks. 
Join us at 13 Princelet Street for this rare public opening to explore the building and find out more about the Landmark Trust. Information about the building will be available with our friendly and knowledgeable staff on hand.
properties.name: 13 Princelet Street with The Landmark Trust

properties.description: Step into the historic charm of 81 Columbia Road Flower Market in East London.  This iconic Victorian terraced house functions as a live/work space for a local artist who has focussed on photographs of London architecture and life.
properties.name: 81 Columbia Road

properties.description:
All Saints was founded in 1871 and is proud to touch the lives of many people in the community through outreach and mission.
The church building is Grade 2 listed and is both beautiful and traditional in style.
properties.name: All Saints Church

properties.description: Sir Howard Hodgkin (1932 – 2017) was one of England’s most celebrated contemporary artists. Abstracted yet allusive, apparently spontaneous but in fact highly controlled, his paintings convey feeling through gesture and colour.  His former studio, converted from a nineteenth-century dairy, sits in the heart of Bloomsbury.
properties.name: Howard Hodgkin Studio

properties.description: St Michael's is a Grade 1 listed building by architect J L Pearson. It was described by the poet John Betjeman as”one of Pearson’s loveliest churches” and Pevsner stated that “The interior is one of Pearson’s finest, and one of the most satisfying of its date anywhere”. There are particularly fine interior furnishings by eminent artists such as Bodley, Temple Moore and Comper.
properties.name: St Michael's Church, Croydon

properties.description: Explore some of the oldest – and newest – parts of London's underground rail infrastructure as you learn about the world’s first passenger underground railway and hear about its impact on the built environment. From saving London from traffic chaos in the 1850s to fuelling its expansion ever since, it's a fascinating tale of human ingenuity – and property speculation!
properties.name: How the tube shaped London

properties.description: Inner Space, London’s oasis of calm and insight is opening its doors during the Open House Festival. We will be offering free short Guided Meditations, short taster seminars and drop-in workshops throughout the weekend. Visitors will also have the opportunity to spend time in our Quiet Room and experience some moments of peace and calm.
properties.name: Inner Space, Meditation Centre, Covent Garden

properties.description: Built between 1690-1720, No. 1 Goodwins Court celebrates 300 years of existence with the completion of its painstaking 10-year restoration. Part of a row of Grade II* Listed buildings within Covent Garden’s Conservation Area, it is a rare survivor of a building type reflecting the conditions of London's Georgian working classes. Goodwins Court was the inspiration for Harry Potter's Diagon Alley.

images.title: Goodwins Court, with bow-fronted shop windows and gas lamps, reflects working-class Georgian London.
Earliest colour scheme using traditional distempers and linseed oil paint over lime plaster and pine

properties.name: 1 Goodwins Court: 10 year Georgian restoration

properties.description:
The University of East London’s Architecture and Visual Arts is a lively School that combines, Architecture, Physical Design and the Visual Arts. This perfect combination of creative programs cross-pollinate, providing a fertile ground for creation, arts and design.
Our presence  will feature guided tours to the state-of-the-art facilities, creative studios, and ‘Way out East’ gallery.
properties.name: University of East London - Architecture and Visual Art

properties.description:
Merchant Taylors' Almshouses. 
The history of this place, the preservation process, and the meticulous restoration of the building.
properties.name: Merchant Taylors' Almshouses

properties.description:
Victorian Tardis
The original house dates from 1864 but was completely redeveloped in 1984 fine tuned in 1993 and in 2023 by three different architects. Double height and open interiors contrast with a Victorian facade
properties.name: 11 Hungerford Road

properties.description: An exquisite three-bedroom apartment is situated on the second floor of a handsome Edwardian block to the east of Marylebone. Redesigned by architect William Smalley, named Disco Flat by him as well related to the fabulous illuminated corridor. I purchased this property a year ago, had changed the interior of it step by step. I would call it a masterclass in the transformative power of material.

images.title: Dining space captured from sitting room

properties.name: Disco Flat

properties.description: Second project by ao-ft located in Walthamstow Village. Reconfiguration of a garden wall into ground-floor extension characterised by a series of high level windows.
properties.name: Barclay Corner

properties.description: St James's Piccadilly is a Grade I listed Christopher Wren church in the heart of the West End. Completed in 1684, and known as the Artists' Church, its interiors include historic works of art by Grinling Gibbons (reredos, organ case and font), postwar Classical interiors by Albert Richardson, and contemporary art by Che Lovelace honouring the 18th-century abolitionist Quobna Ottobah Cugoano.

images.title: St James's Church Piccadilly, seen from Jermyn Street
The lime wood reredos carved by Grinling Gibbons
The River (left) and Passage (right) by Che Lovelace hanging in the narthex at St James's Piccadilly

properties.name: St James's Piccadilly

properties.description: The Old Fire Station is now a thriving community centre run by the Holloway Neighbourhood Group. It has been redeveloped for this purpose, now housing a community room, garden room and hall. The building has many original features (notably on the outside) and even though the usage has changed dramatically it remains an important emergency service for many in the local area.
properties.name: The Old Fire Station

properties.description:
Contemporary Applied Arts, is London’s original multi-disciplinary applied arts gallery.
We are a registered charity and a membership organisation with more than two hundred leading British-based artists working in ceramics, furniture, glass, jewellery, metal, paper, textiles and wood. We view this interdisciplinary approach as a harmonious dialogue between materials & techniques.
properties.name: Contemporary Applied Arts

properties.description: The Northern Croydon tour explores the hometown of Stormzy and Nadia Rose while also visiting The BRIT School and the home of Avril Coleridge Taylor as well as famed recording studios that played a role in Indie, new-wave, reggae and more. This tour highlights the buildings, ranges, diversity, expression, history, art, and passion that has made Croydon a music hub.
properties.name: North Croydon Music Heritage Walking Tour

properties.description: 1960s Modernist townhouse refurbished, revitalised and extended to create a low energy home.
properties.name: Don't Move, Improve! - Chelsea Brut

properties.description: London is the world's first National Park City, and our visitors centre at 109 Fleet Street is the entry point to hundreds of places to visit and things to do across a greener, healthier and wilder London.

images.title: London National Park City visitors centre at 109 Fleet Street looking towards St Paul's Cathedral

properties.name: London National Park City Visitors Centre

properties.description: St Lawrence started life as a hospital and chapel in the 12th century. There is a 15th century tower but the rest of the building was rebuilt in the 19th century. It has been unused and  virtually derelict since the 1960s.  It has been refurbished but is currently empty.
properties.name: St Lawrence

properties.description:
An exploration of Old Lambeth, showing there is more to this district than an association with a 1930s musical and the residence of the Archbishop of Canterbury, this walk reveals links between industry and art, repurposed buildings and  shows hidden gems.
The only United Nations building in London, award winning architecture and unexpected green space are all on the route.

images.title: Lambeth Palace and former St Mary at Lambeth, now the Garden Museum

properties.name: THE LAMBETH WALK

properties.description: Brockley House is a colourful renovation of a mid-century corner house in Lewisham, reimagined by Office S&M Architects for a young family of three. The design draws inspiration from cakes, American diners, and digital art, and creatively reconfigures and extends the house to introduce dynamic light, drama, and a sense of joy throughout.

images.title: Brockley House by Office S&M Architects, photograph by  French + Tye

properties.name: Brockley House

properties.description: The Herbarium is not usually open to public, only to visiting researchers and we would like to open the complex of historic and modern buildings up, prepare displays (on herbarium curation and digitisation of the collection) and arrange guided tours.

images.title: Interior of wing C, first Herbarium extension built in 1877.
The newest Herbarium wing, Wing E, built in 2009

properties.name: Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew - Herbarium

properties.description: Discover Soho in the 1700s and 1800s - a place of bawdy houses, body snatchers and benevolent doctors who rubbed along together in alleyways and elegant townhouses. Soho’s narrow streets have been blighted by cholera and seen some of the country’s first specialist hospitals. Many of its buildings escaped the bombing of WWll and at least in part can be seen today.

images.title: Lou talking outside the Hospital for Women in Soho Square
The Broad Street pump responsible for the 1854 Soho cholera outbreak
Mary Seacole's home after the Crimean War

properties.name: Death, debauchery and doctors in Soho

properties.description:
Enfield Council has been awarded grant funding from the National Heritage Lottery Fund, The Pilgrim Trust and The Enfield Society to understand how the non-conformist chapel in Lavender Hill Cemetery can be conserved and identify potential new uses.

Join us to explore the cemetery, take a look inside the former Chapel and give us your thoughts on its future!

images.title: Interior image of Lavender Hill Non-Conformist Chapel

properties.name: Lavender Hill: Chapel and Community

properties.description: Follow in the footsteps of the Beatles, Coldplay, Alfred Hitchcock and countless others….See what remains of the iconic 1960’s BBC Television Centre and the Gaumont Film Studios  ….plus discover Charles Dickens’ controversial connection to Shepherd’s Bush .
properties.name: ‘Strictly Entertainment’- Shepherd’s Bush 1915-2013

properties.description: On this journey into Soho and St Giles, I want to show the different ways London’s streets are alive with love in all its varied forms. Buildings are often said to be sympathetic or out of place, in keeping or a departure from their surroundings. This tour will explore how the built environment reflects the relationships we conduct with each other.
properties.name: London, adored and explored

properties.description: This two-hour walk covers a number of leading personalities who led the fight back against the Axis Powers, explores preparations for some of the most decisive battles, considers how London became the centre of the free world while not losing sight of how people got on with their lives. This is realised by visiting the locations they worked from or the memorials raised to them.

images.title: Admiralty Citadel - the World War II bunker in the heart of St James's

properties.name: World War 2 in Westminster - a walk

properties.description: Visit our self-built hempcrete studio in the garden. Built by architects Kate & Graham of Commonbond Architects. This is is an experimental project with a focus on sustainability using low-embodied-carbon materials and providing a connection to nature. Hidden away the studio provides a place of calm refuge and offers alternative ways of building using environmentally friendly materials.
properties.name: Gardenhide Studio visit

properties.description: Join this walking tour to discover how post-war architects and planners re-imagined the future of housing, including the low-rise Alexandra and Ainsworth Estate designed by Neave Brown and the high-rise monolith Trellick Tower by  Erno Goldfinger. This walk is not about housing pre-fixed by ‘public’, ‘social’, ‘council’ or ‘local’ – but the concept of housing itself.
properties.name: A tale of two cities - two takes on modernist housing

properties.description: Trace the lost river and discover abandoned island of Channelsea, then visit the newly founded urban oasis of Abbey Gardens on this walk, talk and eat exploration of this hidden history of the tidal Lea Valley and site of  London's now rapidly vanishing industrial past. Consider the opportunity to make new urban green spaces that celebrate both wild and manmade environments in harmony.

images.title: OS Map of 1898 showing Abbey Mills Pumping Station and the island -https://www.remotelondon.com
Abbey Gardens - Community Growing and making - https://www.abbeygardens.org/

properties.name: Channelsea River to Abbey Gardens - Lost + Found Places

properties.description: Up in Smoke - the NOW Gallery Design Commission by artist John Booth and architecture studio CAN, transforms the gallery into a vibrant installation that reveals the rich history of Greenwich Peninsula, through its iconic chimneys. The exhibition combines the duo's distinctive styles: Booth's playful, colourful design aesthetic and CAN's fresh, irreverent approach to architecture.
properties.name: Up in Smoke by John Booth X CAN

properties.description: Join curator William Rees for a tour of sites in Southall with ties to the Martinware collection; from the location of the Martin brothers' studio on the Grand Union Canal, to the lost fountain of Southall Manor House Grounds, to the home of the collection today at Southall Library, Dominion Centre. Participants will get a free Martinware map and view collection items recently placed on view.
properties.name: Martinware Trail in Southall

properties.description:
outhouse gallery is a small, independent, artist run creative space located in Brunswick Park, Camberwell. 
As a former public toilet, the gallery's mission is to be open, public and accessible to both facilitators and visitors - from free exhibitions, live performances, and workshops to providing a space for recording and broadcasting an independent radio station.
properties.name: outhouse gallery

properties.description: Located in the Seven Dials Conservation Area, David Kohn Architects' tiered rooftop extension creates a new family home that responds to the richness of its historic context, the surrounding rooflines, and the robustness of the existing brick warehouse building beneath.
properties.name: Smart's Place

properties.description: The University of West London is offering guided tours of its Ealing site, led by some of our current students, offering the opportunity to discover more about the University’s history and how its facilities have been transformed in recent years.
properties.name: University of West London

properties.description:
Manber Jeffries House is an intricate, single storey, rear and side extension to the ground floor flat of a substantial, semi-detached, Victorian villa in Willesden Green, London.

The project won the RIBA London Small Project of the Year Award 2023, and was shortlisted for the Stephen Lawrence Prize 2023.

Manber Jeffries House | Photography: Hampus Berndtson

Manber Jeffries House | Photography: Hampus Berndtson
Manber Jeffries House | Photography: Hampus Berndtson
